{"title_page": "John Register", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = John Register\n| image         = \n| alt           =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = John Sherman Register<ref name=\"NYT01\">{{cite web\n |title        = Paid Notice: Deaths  BARRETT, DOROTHY PRATT\n |publisher    = New York Times\n |author       = \n |date         = February 12, 1998\n |url          = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/12/classified/paid-notice-deaths-barrett-dorothy-pratt.html}}</ref> \n| birth_date    = February 1, 1939<ref name=\"swart\"/>\n| birth_place   = [[New York]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1996|4|9|1939|2|1}}\n| death_place   = [[Malibu]], [[California]]\n| death_cause = [[Cancer]]\n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| movement      = [[Realism]]\n| training      = \n| field         = Painting\n| works         = \n}}\n'''John Register''' (1939 \u2013 1996) was an American realist painter, noted for paintings with \"a surreal stillness about them.\"<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> \n\n==Background==\nJohn Sherman Register was born February 1, 1939<ref name=\"swart\"/> in New York to Dorothy Deming Pratt Register and Samuel Croft Register.<ref name=\"NYT01\"/> His parents divorced when he was three.<ref name=\"swart\"/> His maternal great-grandfather, [[Charles Pratt]] was one of [[John D. Rockefeller]]'s partners in the formation of the [[Standard Oil Company]] (now Exxon), Charles Pratt & Company in New York and [[Pratt Institute]] in Brooklyn. \n\nRegister graduated from the [[Lawrenceville School]] in New Jersey and the [[University of California]] at Berkeley.  He later studied at the [[California School of Fine Arts]] in San Francisco. After graduating from the University of California, Berkeley, with B.A. in Literature in 1961, he met his wife Catherine Richards in a photography class at The Pasadena Art Center where he was studying commercial art. \n\nIn 1964 the two moved to New York, where Register studied design and television at the [[Pratt Institute]] (founded by his great-grandfather).<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> They married on February 6, 1964 and together had three children Peter, Kate and David. During this period Register pursued a career in advertising at McCaffrey and McCall. In 1972, just after his 33rd birthday,<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> Register left an important client meeting saying he had a dental appointment and never returning.  He subsequently became a full-time painter, moving is family to California. His interests included racing cars and ice-boats, photography, tennis, competitive chess,letter writer, reading, backpacking, fishing, and surfing.<ref name=\"swart\">{{cite web\n |title        = John Register\n |publisher    = SWart\n |author       = \n |date         = February 1, 2000\n |url          = https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/OBITUARY-John-Register-2986924.php}}</ref> \n\nRegister was born with a genetic kidney disease and nearly died numerous times.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>  He had suffered kidney failure 15 years before his death &mdash; ultimately from cancer from kidney transplant rejection drugs.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> In September 1994, he was told he had four to six weeks to live. He lived instead for 18 months, battling cancer until his death in 1996 at the age of 57, in Malibu, California.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\">{{cite web\n |title        = OBITUARY -- John Register\n |publisher    = SFGate\n |author       = Carl Nolte\n |date         = April 11, 1996\n |url          = https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/OBITUARY-John-Register-2986924.php}}</ref> \n\nAt the time of his death, he was survived by his mother, Dorothy Pratt Barrett (then remarried) of Hillsborough, California; his sister, Barbara Pratt Register of Rolling Hills, California; his brother, Eliot Steven Barrett of St. Helena, California; and his three children, Peter, David and Katie; and one grandson.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>\n\n==Work==\nRegister said \"I look for offbeat beauty. I don't know what I'm looking for until I find it. There are things so ugly that I can't paint them. Sometimes I get depressed by that city, and by other cities I visit. But I like the patina of things that have been battered by life\".\nJohn Register's vision of isolated streets, empty coffee shops, long shadows, old hotels, and bus stations \"represent a haunting stillness tinged with regret and hope\", wrote Barnaby Conrad in John Register Persistent Observer.\n\nHe was honored with a retrospective of his career in 1999.\n\nRegister studied with the portrait painter Raymond Kinstler and landscape painter [[Lennart Anderson]].<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> He had his first show in Los Angeles in 1975 and received the Francis J. Greenburger Foundation Award from the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Museum]].<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>\n\nHe has shown almost exclusively at the Modernism Gallery in San Francisco. A show of drawings by Mr. Register and [[Edward Hopper]] took place in 1996. The [[San Jose Museum of Art]] hosted a major retrospective show of Mr. Register's work in the fall of 1997.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> \n \nRegister's work was used, and credited, as the inspiration for the video for \"[[Turn My Head]]\" by the band [[Live (band)|Live]] in 1997. His paintings were also featured in the movie [[In Her Shoes (2005 film)|''In Her Shoes'' (2005 film)]].  Director [[Curtis Hanson]] liked the \"loneliness\" that Register's paintings suggested for the feel of the film.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* [[Barnaby Conrad III|Conrad, Barnaby III]]. ''John Register: Persistent Observer.'' Duane Press, 1999.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.modernisminc.com/artists/John_REGISTER/ Register at Modernism.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928175116/http://www.sjmusart.org/content/collection/highlights/paintings/item_info.phtml?itemID=24&typeID=paintings ''Desert Landscape'' at the San Jose Museum of Art.]\n*[http://artregister.com/SeavestIntroductiontoCollection/Catalogue/RegisterConversation.html ''The Conversation'' at the Seavest Collection.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Register, John}}\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = John Register\n| image         = \n| alt           =\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = John Sherman Register<ref name=\"NYT01\">{{cite web\n |title        = Paid Notice: Deaths  BARRETT, DOROTHY PRATT\n |publisher    = New York Times\n |author       = \n |date         = February 12, 1998\n |url          = https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/12/classified/paid-notice-deaths-barrett-dorothy-pratt.html}}</ref> \n| birth_date    = February 1, 1939<ref name=\"swart\"/>\n| birth_place   = [[New York]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1996|4|9|1939|2|1}}\n| death_place   = [[Malibu]], [[California]]\n| death_cause = [[Cancer]]\n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| movement      = [[Realism]]\n| training      = \n| field         = Painting\n| works         = \n}}\n'''John Register''' (1939 \u2013 1996) was an American realist painter, noted for paintings with \"a surreal stillness about them.\"<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> \n\n==Background==\nJohn Sherman Register was born February 1, 1939<ref name=\"swart\"/> in New York to Dorothy Deming Pratt Register and Samuel Croft Register.<ref name=\"NYT01\"/> His maternal great-grandfather, [[Charles Pratt]] was one of [[John D. Rockefeller]]'s partners in the formation of the [[Standard Oil Company]] (now Exxon), Charles Pratt & Company in New York and [[Pratt Institute]] in Brooklyn. \n\nRegister graduated from the [[Lawrenceville School]] in New Jersey and the [[University of California]] at Berkeley.  He later studied at the [[California School of Fine Arts]] in San Francisco. After graduating from the University of California, Berkeley, with B.A. in Literature in 1961, he met his wife Catherine Richards in a photography class at The Pasadena Art Center where he was studying commercial art. \n\nIn 1964 the two moved to New York, where Register studied design and television at the [[Pratt Institute]] (founded by his great-grandfather).<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> They married on February 6, 1964 and together had three children Peter, Kate and David. During this period Register pursued a career in advertising at McCaffrey and McCall. In 1972, just after his 33rd birthday,<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> Register left an important client meeting saying he had a dental appointment and never returning.  He subsequently became a full-time painter, moving is family to California. His interests included racing cars and ice-boats, photography, tennis, competitive chess,letter writer, reading, backpacking, fishing, and surfing.<ref name=\"swart\">{{cite web\n |title        = John Register\n |publisher    = SWart\n |author       = \n |date         = February 1, 2000\n |url          = https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/OBITUARY-John-Register-2986924.php}}</ref> \n\nRegister was born with a genetic kidney disease and nearly died numerous times.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>  He had suffered kidney failure 15 years before his death &mdash; ultimately from cancer from kidney transplant rejection drugs.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> In September 1994, he was told he had four to six weeks to live. He lived instead for 18 months, battling cancer until his death in 1996 at the age of 57, in Malibu, California.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\">{{cite web\n |title        = OBITUARY -- John Register\n |publisher    = SFGate\n |author       = Carl Nolte\n |date         = April 11, 1996\n |url          = https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/OBITUARY-John-Register-2986924.php}}</ref> \n\nAt the time of his death, he was survived by his mother, Dorothy Pratt Barrett (then remarried) of Hillsborough, California; his sister, Barbara Pratt Register of Rolling Hills, California; his brother, Eliot Steven Barrett of St. Helena, California; and his three children, Peter, David and Katie; and one grandson.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>\n\n==Work==\nRegister said \"I look for offbeat beauty. I don't know what I'm looking for until I find it. There are things so ugly that I can't paint them. Sometimes I get depressed by that city, and by other cities I visit. But I like the patina of things that have been battered by life\".\nJohn Register's vision of isolated streets, empty coffee shops, long shadows, old hotels, and bus stations \"represent a haunting stillness tinged with regret and hope\", wrote Barnaby Conrad in John Register Persistent Observer.\n\nHe was honored with a retrospective of his career in 1999.\n\nRegister studied with the portrait painter Raymond Kinstler and landscape painter [[Lennart Anderson]].<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> He had his first show in Los Angeles in 1975 and received the Francis J. Greenburger Foundation Award from the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Museum]].<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/>\n\nHe has shown almost exclusively at the Modernism Gallery in San Francisco. A show of drawings by Mr. Register and [[Edward Hopper]] took place in 1996. The [[San Jose Museum of Art]] hosted a major retrospective show of Mr. Register's work in the fall of 1997.<ref name=\"obitsfgate\"/> \n \nRegister's work was used, and credited, as the inspiration for the video for \"[[Turn My Head]]\" by the band [[Live (band)|Live]] in 1997. His paintings were also featured in the movie [[In Her Shoes (2005 film)|''In Her Shoes'' (2005 film)]].  Director [[Curtis Hanson]] liked the \"loneliness\" that Register's paintings suggested for the feel of the film.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n* [[Barnaby Conrad III|Conrad, Barnaby III]]. ''John Register: Persistent Observer.'' Duane Press, 1999.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.modernisminc.com/artists/John_REGISTER/ Register at Modernism.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928175116/http://www.sjmusart.org/content/collection/highlights/paintings/item_info.phtml?itemID=24&typeID=paintings ''Desert Landscape'' at the San Jose Museum of Art.]\n*[http://artregister.com/SeavestIntroductiontoCollection/Catalogue/RegisterConversation.html ''The Conversation'' at the Seavest Collection.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Register, John}}\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Register"}
{"title_page": "No Way Jose (wrestler)", "text_new": "{{short description|Dominican-American wrestler}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = No Way Jose\n|image       = No Way Jose (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = No Way Jose in April 2018\n|birth_name  = Levis Valenzuela Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1988|05|30}}\n|birth_place = [[Durham, North Carolina]], U.S.\n|residence   =\n|names       = Levis Valenzuela Jr.<ref name=owow/><br>Manny Garcia<ref name=owow>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/n/no-way-jose/|title=No Way Jose OWW|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br>'''No Way Jose'''<ref name=owow/>\n|height      = 6 ft 3 in<ref name=WWEbio>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/nowayjose|title=No Way Jose|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref>\n|weight      = 245 lb<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|billed      = [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]]<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|trainer     = Roy Wilkins<br>[[Trevor Lee]]<ref name=\"Miamiherald\">{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/fighting/article18388127.html|title= WWE welcomes new NXT recruits: Introducing Levis Valenzuela Jr.|work=Miami Herald|accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref>\n|debut       = May 17, 2013<ref name=\"owow\"/>\n|retired     = \n}}\n'''Levis Valenzuela Jr.'''<ref name=\"WWEinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/levis-valenzuela-jr-interview|title= Levis Valenzuela Jr. proud to represent Dominican Republic in NXT|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=WWE.com}}</ref> (born May 30, 1988) is an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], Best known for his time with [[WWE]], where he performed under the [[ring name]] '''No Way Jose'''.\n\nValenzuela debuted in May 2013, wrestling under the name '''Manny Garcia''' for North Carolina promotion [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]], where he became a two-time [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship|CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Champion]]. He signed with WWE in 2015, wrestling in its developmental territory [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] before being called up to the main roster in April 2018.\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n=== Independent circuit (2013\u20132015) ===\n[[File:Manny Garcia 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Garcia in 2014]]\nValenzuela made his debut in [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]] as '''Manny Garcia''' on May 17, 2013. Manny lost his debut match against [[Ric Converse]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://cwf247.com/wp/manny-garcia-joins-nxt/|title=Manny Garcia Joins NXT|work=cwf.com|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On May 3, 2014, he defeated Mark James to win the [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]].<ref name=CWFTitle>{{cite web |url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/tvcwf3.html |title=CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Title |author=Tanabe, Hisaharu |year=2011 |work=Solie's Title Histories |publisher=Solie.org |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On December 6, 2014, Manny lost the title to Chris Lea.<ref name=CWFTitle/> On December 27, 2014, Manny re-captured the TV Championship.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://indypowerrankingsipr.wordpress.com/2014/12/28/1227-cwf-mid-atlantic-battlecade-xv-results/ |title = 12/27 CWF Mid-Atlantic Battlecade XV Results|date = December 28, 2014}}</ref> On March 21, 2015, Manny lost his title in a Fatal 4 Way where Chet Sterling came out as victorious.<ref name=cagematch/> In addition to CWF Mid-Atlantic, Garcia also appeared for promotions including Fire Star Pro Wrestling and [[OMEGA Championship Wrestling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_83652.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - SHOW RESULTS 2/28 OMEGA in Durham, N.C.: Jeff Hardy new OMEGA champion, Mick Foley, Gallows vs. Dreamer, more|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== WWE ===\n====NXT (2015\u20132018) ====\nIn April 2015, it was reported that Valenzuela signed a contract with WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-News-The-newest-NXT-class-includes-an-independent-standout-and-ten-others-41786|title=WWE News: The newest NXT class includes an independent standout and ten others|publisher=}}</ref> On April 10, 2015, Valenzuela was announced as one of 11 new signings to begin training at the [[WWE Performance Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/wwe-performance-center-welcomes-new-class-of-recruits|title=WWE Performance Center welcomes new class of recruits|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref> Wrestling under his real name, Valenzuela made his first appearance on ''[[WWE NXT (TV series)|NXT]]'' as an [[Job (professional wrestling)|enhancement talent]], teaming with [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias Samson]] in a tag team match, losing to [[American Alpha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwenxtreport/article_86582.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - WWE NXT RESULTS 7/29: Blake & Murphy defend NXT Tag Titles, Kevin Owens \"fined,\" Charlotte in action, Jesse Sorensen, more|publisher=}}</ref> Valenzuela then began to make frequent appearances at [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] [[house show]]s for the rest of 2015 and the early part of 2016.<ref name=cagematch/>\n\nIn April 2016, vignettes began to air hyping the debut of Valenzuela, now repackaged as '''No Way Jose'''. He made his official debut on the April 20, 2016 episode of ''NXT'', defeating [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]]. On the June 22 episode of ''NXT'', Jose interrupted [[Austin Aries]] during his interview backstage and told him to be positive following Aries' loss at [[NXT TakeOver: The End]]. Later that night, Jose defeated Josh Woods. Aries then came out and ended up dancing with Jose, but he then attacked Jose. After weeks of missing ''NXT'', Jose attacked Aries after Aries' match on the July 20 episode of ''NXT''. Jose rushed Aries outside into the locker room. Aries defeated Jose at [[NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn II]].\n\nThen, Jose entered a feud with [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]] and the [[Sanity (professional wrestling)|SAnitY]] faction by calling them out after they interrupted a match between [[Rich Swann]] and [[Kona Reeves]]. This led to an assault on Jose. On the November 30 episode of ''NXT'', Jose faced Eric Young in a losing effort. On the December 7 episode of ''NXT'', Jose and Rich Swann faced the team of Eric Young and [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]] again in a losing effort.<ref name=debut>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/22/420-wwe-nxt-tv-results-jamess-full-report-on-joe-vs-crews-main-event-enzo-cass-face-nxt-tag-champs-nia-jax-no-way-jose-debuts/|title=4/20 WWE NXT TV Results - James's Full Report on Joe vs. Crews main event, Enzo & Cass face NXT tag champs, Nia Jax, No Way Jose debuts -|publisher=|date=April 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NXTBrooklynII\">{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title=8/20 \"WWE NXT Takeover: Brooklyn\" Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/08/20/820-wwe-nxt-takeover-brooklyn-results-caldwells-ongoing-live-report/|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> Jose continued to feud with SAnitY, forming an alliance with [[Tye Dillinger]] and [[Roderick Strong]] to battle the faction in early 2017. He was scheduled to team with Dillinger, Strong and [[Ruby Riott|Ruby Riot]] against SAnitY at [[NXT TakeOver: Orlando]] but he was attacked by Sanity before the show. He was replaced by [[Kassius Ohno]] in the match, which was eventually won by SAnitY.\n\n==== Raw (2018\u20132020) ====\nOn the April 9 episode of [[WWE Raw|''Raw'']], the first after [[WrestleMania 34]], Jose made his main roster debut, defeating [[Job (professional wrestling)|local talent]] John Skyler in a [[glossary of professional wrestling terms#squash|squash match]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=No Way Jose def. John Skyler|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-09/article/no-way-jose-def-john-skyler|website=WWE.com|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> Jose picked up an [[Upset (competition)|upset victory]] against [[Baron Corbin]] on the April 30 episode of ''Raw'', after interference from [[Titus O'Neil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-30/article/titus-oneil-no-way-jose-baron-corbin|title=No Way Jose def. Baron Corbin|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=April 30, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> This would lead to Jose teaming with O'Neil and [[Apollo Crews]] to face Corbin and [[The Revival (professional wrestling)|The Revival]] on the May 7 episode of ''Raw'' in a losing effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/103879-may-7-2018-mitb-qualifying-matches-uniondale/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 5/7/18 (Two Triple Threat Money in the Bank Qualifying Matches)|work=WrestleView|first=Mike|last=Tedesco|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> He failed to qualify for the [[Money in the Bank ladder match|Men's Money in the Bank ladder match]] in a triple threat match against Corbin and the eventual winner [[Bobby Roode]] on the May 14 episode of ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagesideseats.com/wwe/2018/5/14/17354444/bobby-roode-wins-into-mens-money-in-the-bank-ladder-match-wwe-raw|title=Bobby Roode wins his way into the men's Money in the Bank ladder match|last=Messano|first=Tommy|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref> On the May 21 episode of ''Raw'', Jose was defeated by Corbin to end their feud.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-05-21/article/baron-corbin-def-no-way-jose|title=Baron Corbin def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose then started a feud with [[Mojo Rawley]]. After losing  to Rawley on the June 18 episode of ''Raw'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-06-18/article/mojo-rawley-def-no-way-jose|title=Mojo Rawley def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose would ask for a rematch, only to be constantly denied one by Rawley for the next three weeks. Jose finally got his rematch on the July 9 episode of ''Raw'', however he would once again be defeated by Rawley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/07/09/heydorns-wwe-raw-report-7-9-alt-perspective-coverage-of-the-live-show-including-the-final-hype-for-extreme-rules-brock-lesnar-fallout-and-more/|title=HEYDORN'S WWE RAW REPORT 7/9: Alt Perspective coverage of the live show including the final hype for Extreme Rules, Rollins vs. McIntyre, and more|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Zack|last=Heydorn|date=July 9, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Afterwards, Jose did not compete on ''Raw'' for four months, instead regularly appearing on [[WWE Main Event|''Main Event'']]. Jose returned to ''Raw'' on November 26, where he was defeated by [[Jinder Mahal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-11-26/article/jinder-mahal-def-no-way-jose|title=Jinder Mahal def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=November 26, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nJose made his [[Royal Rumble match|Royal Rumble]] debut at the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|namesake event]] on January 27, 2019, only to be eliminated in two seconds by [[Samoa Joe]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Seth Rollins won the 30-Man Royal Rumble Match|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/2019/2019-mens-royal-rumble-match-\nresults|publisher=WWE|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 15th April it was announced on WWE\u2019s official website that Kanellis was released as well as various other superstars.\n\n==Other media==\nValenzuela made his WWE video game debut as a playable character in ''[[WWE 2K18]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k18/article/wwe-2k18-roster-playable-character-list|title=WWE 2K18 roster: Meet the Superstars joining the list of playable characters|author=WWE Staff|work=WWE.com|publisher=[[WWE]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref> and subsequently appears in ''[[WWE 2K19]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nordic.ign.com/m/xbox-one-gaming-hardware/18381/news/wwe-2k19-roster-reveal-75-playable-superstars-announced |title=WWE 2K19 Roster Reveal: 75 Playable Superstars Announced |last=Fowler |first=Matt |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n* '''[[CWF Mid-Atlantic]]'''\n** [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]] ([[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship#title history|2 times]])<ref name=CWFTitle/>\n* '''Fire Star Pro Wrestling'''\n** FSPW South Eastern Championship (1 time)<ref name=cagematch>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247&name=Manny+Garcia|title=No Way Jose|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**PWI ranked him No. 200 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2018|work=cagematch.net}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{wwe superstars|nowayjose|No Way Jose}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247 No Way Jose on Cagematch.net]\n\n{{WWE personnel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:No Way Jose}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Santo Domingo]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American people of Dominican Republic descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dominican-American wrestler}}\n{{Use American English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = No Way Jose\n|image       = No Way Jose (cropped).jpg\n|caption     = No Way Jose in April 2018\n|birth_name  = Levis Valenzuela Jr.\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1988|05|30}}\n|birth_place = [[Durham, North Carolina]], U.S.\n|residence   =\n|names       = Levis Valenzuela Jr.<ref name=owow/><br>Manny Garcia<ref name=owow>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/n/no-way-jose/|title=No Way Jose OWW|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br>'''No Way Jose'''<ref name=owow/>\n|height      = 6 ft 3 in<ref name=WWEbio>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/nowayjose|title=No Way Jose|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref>\n|weight      = 245 lb<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|billed      = [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]]<ref name=WWEbio/>\n|trainer     = Roy Wilkins<br>[[Trevor Lee]]<ref name=\"Miamiherald\">{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/fighting/article18388127.html|title= WWE welcomes new NXT recruits: Introducing Levis Valenzuela Jr.|work=Miami Herald|accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref>\n|debut       = May 17, 2013<ref name=\"owow\"/>\n|retired     = \n}}\n'''Levis Valenzuela Jr.'''<ref name=\"WWEinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/levis-valenzuela-jr-interview|title= Levis Valenzuela Jr. proud to represent Dominican Republic in NXT|accessdate=May 9, 2016|publisher=WWE.com}}</ref> (born May 30, 1988) is an American [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]], Best known for his time with [[WWE]], where he performed under the [[ring name]] '''No Way Jose'''.\n\nValenzuela debuted in May 2013, wrestling under the name '''Manny Garcia''' for North Carolina promotion [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]], where he became a two-time [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship|CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Champion]]. He signed with WWE in 2015, wrestling in its developmental territory [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] before being called up to the main roster in April 2018.\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n=== Independent circuit (2013\u20132015) ===\n[[File:Manny Garcia 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Garcia in 2014]]\nValenzuela made his debut in [[CWF Mid-Atlantic]] as '''Manny Garcia''' on May 17, 2013. Manny lost his debut match against [[Ric Converse]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://cwf247.com/wp/manny-garcia-joins-nxt/|title=Manny Garcia Joins NXT|work=cwf.com|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On May 3, 2014, he defeated Mark James to win the [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]].<ref name=CWFTitle>{{cite web |url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/tvcwf3.html |title=CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Title |author=Tanabe, Hisaharu |year=2011 |work=Solie's Title Histories |publisher=Solie.org |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> On December 6, 2014, Manny lost the title to Chris Lea.<ref name=CWFTitle/> On December 27, 2014, Manny re-captured the TV Championship.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://indypowerrankingsipr.wordpress.com/2014/12/28/1227-cwf-mid-atlantic-battlecade-xv-results/ |title = 12/27 CWF Mid-Atlantic Battlecade XV Results|date = December 28, 2014}}</ref> On March 21, 2015, Manny lost his title in a Fatal 4 Way where Chet Sterling came out as victorious.<ref name=cagematch/> In addition to CWF Mid-Atlantic, Garcia also appeared for promotions including Fire Star Pro Wrestling and [[OMEGA Championship Wrestling]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/Arena_Reports_10/article_83652.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - SHOW RESULTS 2/28 OMEGA in Durham, N.C.: Jeff Hardy new OMEGA champion, Mick Foley, Gallows vs. Dreamer, more|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n=== WWE ===\n====NXT (2015\u20132018) ====\nIn April 2015, it was reported that Valenzuela signed a contract with WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-News-The-newest-NXT-class-includes-an-independent-standout-and-ten-others-41786|title=WWE News: The newest NXT class includes an independent standout and ten others|publisher=}}</ref> On April 10, 2015, Valenzuela was announced as one of 11 new signings to begin training at the [[WWE Performance Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/wwe-performance-center-welcomes-new-class-of-recruits|title=WWE Performance Center welcomes new class of recruits|work=www.wwe.com}}</ref> Wrestling under his real name, Valenzuela made his first appearance on ''[[WWE NXT (TV series)|NXT]]'' as an [[Job (professional wrestling)|enhancement talent]], teaming with [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias Samson]] in a tag team match, losing to [[American Alpha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/wwenxtreport/article_86582.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - WWE NXT RESULTS 7/29: Blake & Murphy defend NXT Tag Titles, Kevin Owens \"fined,\" Charlotte in action, Jesse Sorensen, more|publisher=}}</ref> Valenzuela then began to make frequent appearances at [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] [[house show]]s for the rest of 2015 and the early part of 2016.<ref name=cagematch/>\n\nIn April 2016, vignettes began to air hyping the debut of Valenzuela, now repackaged as '''No Way Jose'''. He made his official debut on the April 20, 2016 episode of ''NXT'', defeating [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]]. On the June 22 episode of ''NXT'', Jose interrupted [[Austin Aries]] during his interview backstage and told him to be positive following Aries' loss at [[NXT TakeOver: The End]]. Later that night, Jose defeated Josh Woods. Aries then came out and ended up dancing with Jose, but he then attacked Jose. After weeks of missing ''NXT'', Jose attacked Aries after Aries' match on the July 20 episode of ''NXT''. Jose rushed Aries outside into the locker room. Aries defeated Jose at [[NXT TakeOver: Brooklyn II]].\n\nThen, Jose entered a feud with [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]] and the [[Sanity (professional wrestling)|SAnitY]] faction by calling them out after they interrupted a match between [[Rich Swann]] and [[Kona Reeves]]. This led to an assault on Jose. On the November 30 episode of ''NXT'', Jose faced Eric Young in a losing effort. On the December 7 episode of ''NXT'', Jose and Rich Swann faced the team of Eric Young and [[Alexander Wolfe (wrestler)|Alexander Wolfe]] again in a losing effort.<ref name=debut>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/04/22/420-wwe-nxt-tv-results-jamess-full-report-on-joe-vs-crews-main-event-enzo-cass-face-nxt-tag-champs-nia-jax-no-way-jose-debuts/|title=4/20 WWE NXT TV Results - James's Full Report on Joe vs. Crews main event, Enzo & Cass face NXT tag champs, Nia Jax, No Way Jose debuts -|publisher=|date=April 23, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NXTBrooklynII\">{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title=8/20 \"WWE NXT Takeover: Brooklyn\" Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Live Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/08/20/820-wwe-nxt-takeover-brooklyn-results-caldwells-ongoing-live-report/|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> Jose continued to feud with SAnitY, forming an alliance with [[Tye Dillinger]] and [[Roderick Strong]] to battle the faction in early 2017. He was scheduled to team with Dillinger, Strong and [[Ruby Riott|Ruby Riot]] against SAnitY at [[NXT TakeOver: Orlando]] but he was attacked by Sanity before the show. He was replaced by [[Kassius Ohno]] in the match, which was eventually won by SAnitY.\n\n==== Raw (2018\u20132020) ====\nOn the April 9 episode of [[WWE Raw|''Raw'']], the first after [[WrestleMania 34]], Jose made his main roster debut, defeating [[Job (professional wrestling)|local talent]] John Skyler in a [[glossary of professional wrestling terms#squash|squash match]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=No Way Jose def. John Skyler|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-09/article/no-way-jose-def-john-skyler|website=WWE.com|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> Jose picked up an [[Upset (competition)|upset victory]] against [[Baron Corbin]] on the April 30 episode of ''Raw'', after interference from [[Titus O'Neil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-04-30/article/titus-oneil-no-way-jose-baron-corbin|title=No Way Jose def. Baron Corbin|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=April 30, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> This would lead to Jose teaming with O'Neil and [[Apollo Crews]] to face Corbin and [[The Revival (professional wrestling)|The Revival]] on the May 7 episode of ''Raw'' in a losing effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-raw-results/103879-may-7-2018-mitb-qualifying-matches-uniondale/|title=WWE RAW Results \u2013 5/7/18 (Two Triple Threat Money in the Bank Qualifying Matches)|work=WrestleView|first=Mike|last=Tedesco|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> He failed to qualify for the [[Money in the Bank ladder match|Men's Money in the Bank ladder match]] in a triple threat match against Corbin and the eventual winner [[Bobby Roode]] on the May 14 episode of ''Raw''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagesideseats.com/wwe/2018/5/14/17354444/bobby-roode-wins-into-mens-money-in-the-bank-ladder-match-wwe-raw|title=Bobby Roode wins his way into the men's Money in the Bank ladder match|last=Messano|first=Tommy|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref> On the May 21 episode of ''Raw'', Jose was defeated by Corbin to end their feud.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-05-21/article/baron-corbin-def-no-way-jose|title=Baron Corbin def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose then started a feud with [[Mojo Rawley]]. After losing  to Rawley on the June 18 episode of ''Raw'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-06-18/article/mojo-rawley-def-no-way-jose|title=Mojo Rawley def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=June 18, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Jose would ask for a rematch, only to be constantly denied one by Rawley for the next three weeks. Jose finally got his rematch on the July 9 episode of ''Raw'', however he would once again be defeated by Rawley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2018/07/09/heydorns-wwe-raw-report-7-9-alt-perspective-coverage-of-the-live-show-including-the-final-hype-for-extreme-rules-brock-lesnar-fallout-and-more/|title=HEYDORN'S WWE RAW REPORT 7/9: Alt Perspective coverage of the live show including the final hype for Extreme Rules, Rollins vs. McIntyre, and more|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|first=Zack|last=Heydorn|date=July 9, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> Afterwards, Jose did not compete on ''Raw'' for four months, instead regularly appearing on [[WWE Main Event|''Main Event'']]. Jose returned to ''Raw'' on November 26, where he was defeated by [[Jinder Mahal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2018-11-26/article/jinder-mahal-def-no-way-jose|title=Jinder Mahal def. No Way Jose|work=WWE|first=Anthony|last=Benigno|date=November 26, 2018|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nJose made his [[Royal Rumble match|Royal Rumble]] debut at the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|namesake event]] on January 27, 2019, only to be eliminated in two seconds by [[Samoa Joe]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Seth Rollins won the 30-Man Royal Rumble Match|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/2019/2019-mens-royal-rumble-match-\nresults|publisher=WWE|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 15th April that it was announced on WWE\u2019s official website that Kanellis was released as well as various other superstars.\n\nHe was released on April 15 2020, due to Covid-19 cutbacks\n\n==Other media==\nValenzuela made his WWE video game debut as a playable character in ''[[WWE 2K18]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k18/article/wwe-2k18-roster-playable-character-list|title=WWE 2K18 roster: Meet the Superstars joining the list of playable characters|author=WWE Staff|work=WWE.com|publisher=[[WWE]]|location=[[Stamford, Connecticut]]|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref> and subsequently appears in ''[[WWE 2K19]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nordic.ign.com/m/xbox-one-gaming-hardware/18381/news/wwe-2k19-roster-reveal-75-playable-superstars-announced |title=WWE 2K19 Roster Reveal: 75 Playable Superstars Announced |last=Fowler |first=Matt |publisher=[[IGN]] |date=August 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n* '''[[CWF Mid-Atlantic]]'''\n** [[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship]] ([[CWF Mid-Atlantic Television Championship#title history|2 times]])<ref name=CWFTitle/>\n* '''Fire Star Pro Wrestling'''\n** FSPW South Eastern Championship (1 time)<ref name=cagematch>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247&name=Manny+Garcia|title=No Way Jose|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**PWI ranked him No. 200 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2018|work=cagematch.net}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{wwe superstars|nowayjose|No Way Jose}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=15247 No Way Jose on Cagematch.net]\n\n{{WWE personnel}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:No Way Jose}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Santo Domingo]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American people of Dominican Republic descent]]\n", "name_user": "Ghaithx", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRaw (2018\u20132020)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/No_Way_Jose_(wrestler)"}
{"title_page": "Metro Transit (Minnesota)", "text_new": "{{For|other systems of the same name|Metro Transit (disambiguation)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2008}}\n\n{{Infobox bus transit\n| name            = Metro Transit\n| logo            = Metro Transit logo.svg\n| logo_size       = 250\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_caption   = Metro Transit operates public transit in four different modes in the Minneapolis\u2013St. Paul area.\n| parent          = [[Metropolitan Council]]\n| founded         = 1967\n| headquarters    = [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]], United States\n| locale          = [[Minneapolis \u2013 Saint Paul]]\n| service_type    = [[Transit bus]]<br/>[[Bus rapid transit]]<br/>[[Light rail]]<br/>[[Commuter rail]]<br/>[[Paratransit]]\n| routes          = 127 bus<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/metro-transit-facts|title=Metro Transit 2017 Facts|publisher=Metro Transit|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref><br/>2 bus rapid transit<br/>2 light rail<br/>1 commuter rail\n| fleet           = 514 diesel buses<br/>133 hybrid-electric buses<br/>13 rapid buses<br/>64 coach buses<br/>185 Articulated buses<br/>91 light rail vehicles<br/>6 locomotives<br/>18 rail coaches\n| ridership       = 260,486 (2018)<ref name=\"apta-stats\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/metro-transit-facts|title=Metro Transit 2017 Facts|publisher=Metro Transit|accessdate=September 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| leader_type     = General Manager\n| operator        = Metro Transit\n| leader          = Wes Kooistra\n| website         = http://www.metrotransit.org/\n}}\n\n'''Metro Transit''' is the primary [[public transportation]] operator in the [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]] area of the U.S. state of [[Minnesota]] and the largest operator in the state. The system is a division of the [[Metropolitan Council]], the region's [[metropolitan planning organization]] (MPO), averaging 264,347 riders each weekday, carrying 90% to 95% of the transit riders in the region on a combined network of regular-route [[bus]]es, [[light rail]] and [[commuter rail]].<ref name=\"about\"/> The remainder of Twin Cities transit ridership is generally split among suburban \u201copt-out\u201d carriers operating out of cities that have chosen not to participate in the Metro Transit network. The biggest opt-out providers are [[Minnesota Valley Transit Authority]] (MVTA), [[Maple Grove Transit]] and [[Southwest Transit]] (SW Transit). The [[University of Minnesota]] also operates a [[University of Minnesota Campus Shuttle|campus shuttle system]] that coordinates routes with Metro Transit services.\n\nIn 2017, buses carried about 68% of the system's passengers. Just above 16% of ridership was concentrated on Metro Transit's busiest route, the [[Green Line (Minnesota)|Green Line]] light rail. The region's other light rail line, the [[Blue Line (Minnesota)|Blue Line]], fell close behind, carrying 13% of Metro Transit passengers. Nearly 2% rode the [[A Line (Minnesota)|A Line]] arterial rapid bus line. The remaining approximately 1% rode the [[Northstar Commuter Rail]] service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/rail-lines-set-records-as-metro-transit-ridership-tops-819-million-in-2017|title=Rail lines set records as Metro Transit ridership tops 81.9 million in 2017 - Metro Transit|website=www.metrotransit.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> In 2015, Metro Transit saw its highest yearly ridership ever, with a total of 85.8 million trips, 62.1 million (72%) of which were on buses. The remaining 23.7 million (28%) of passengers traveled on the region's rail lines, including the recently opened [[Green Line (Minnesota)|Green Line]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/Data/Sites/1/media/about/facts/2015/2015_metrotransit_facts.pdf|title=2015 Metro Transit Facts|access-date=May 10, 2018}}</ref> The single-day ridership record is 369,626, set on September 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite news | newspaper = [[Star Tribune]] | url = http://www.startribune.com/vikings-twins-traffic-fears-help-metro-transit-shatter-single-day-ridership-record/392920421/ | title = Vikings, Twins, traffic fears help Metro Transit shatter single-day ridership record | last = Harlow | first = Tim | date = September 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nMetro Transit drivers and vehicle maintenance personnel are organized through the [[Amalgamated Transit Union]]. The agency also contracts with private providers such as [[First Transit]] to offer paratansit services which operate under the Metro Mobility brand.\n\n==History==\nThe agency was established by the [[Minnesota State Legislature]] in 1967 as the '''Metropolitan Transit Commission''' ('''MTC''').<ref>Christopher, Mary Kay. Bus Transit Service in Land Development Planning. Transportation Research Board, 2006.</ref> MTC's operations were moved under the auspices of the [[Metropolitan Council]] in 1994, prompting a name change to \u201cMetropolitan Council Transit Operations\u201d and then, in 1998, to Metro Transit. The organization traces its history back to the 19th-century [[streetcar]] systems of the region through the acquisition in 1970 of the [[Twin City Rapid Transit|Twin City Lines]] bus system from businessman [[Carl Pohlad]]. At the time of the acquisition, Twin City Lines had 635 buses: 75% of those were over 15 years old and 86 buses were so old that they were banned from operating in Minneapolis. MTC acquired 465 new buses over the next five years and built many new bus shelters.<ref name=\"met-council-40\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrocouncil.org/about/metcouncilhistory.pdf|title=A bold experiment: the Metropolitan Council at 40|publisher=Metropolitan Council|accessdate=December 16, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613070633/http://metrocouncil.org/about/MetCouncilHistory.pdf|archivedate=June 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\nShortly thereafter, a long battle began to return rail transit to the region and efforts for additional lines continue at a snail's pace. It took 32 years to see the first line implemented. In 1972, the Regional Fixed Guideway Study for MTC proposed a $1.3 billion 37- or 57-mile (sources differ) [[Heavy rail#Heavy rail|heavy-rail]] [[rapid transit]] system, but the then-separate Metropolitan Council disagreed with that idea\u2014refusing to even look at the plan\u2014and continuing political battles prevented its implementation. The Met Council had its own plans for [[bus rapid transit]] in the Cities. Another system using smaller [[people mover]]s was proposed in the 1975 Small Vehicle Fixed Guideway Study and gained the most traction with the [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]] city council, but was eventually dropped in 1980. In the 1980s, [[light rail]] was proposed as an alternative and several possible corridors were identified, including the [[Green Line (Minnesota)|Central Corridor]], for which a draft [[environmental impact statement]] (DEIS) was drawn up in 1982.<ref name=\"met-council-40\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.citypages.com/blotter/2008/05/a_train_between.php|title=A train linking Minneapolis and St. Paul? We had that scoop in 1984|work=City Pages|author=Jeff Severns Guntzel|date=May 19, 2008|accessdate=2010-02-17|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100217082303/http://blogs.citypages.com/blotter/2008/05/a_train_between.php|archivedate=February 17, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=ALL ABOARD: For the Transit Study that Never Ends|work=City Pages|date=September 5, 1984}}</ref> However, it was another two decades before the [[Blue Line (Minnesota)|Blue Line]] light rail line began operation on June 26, 2004, by then, just over 50 years since the last regular-service streetcar ran on June 19, 1954, under the old Twin City Lines. Heavy-rail commuter service began on November 14, 2009, with the [[Northstar Line]]. The 2010s decade may finally see several new lines open.\n\n[[Image:Metro Transit-University Avenue-20081002.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Bus and driver on University Avenue in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]], near Saint Paul]]\nMetro Transit does not cover the whole Twin Cities area. Bus service in the suburbs was being cut back in the early 1980s and suburb-to-suburb service was limited (an issue that remains today). In 1986, cities and counties in the seven-county metropolitan area were given the option to run their own bus services and leave the MTC system. About 17.5% of the area which has regular route transit service is served by these six other \u201copt out\u201d transit systems. About 5% of the system is contracted to private transit providers.\n\nIn the mid-2000s decade, the system claimed to have a safety record five times better than the national average.\n\n==Funding==\nMetro Transit currently receives the majority of its funding from the State Motor Vehicle Sales Tax, the State General Fund, fares and federal revenues. Metro Transit prepares an annual calendar budget, but most of its [[subsidy]] comes from state funds, on a July 1 biennial budget. Between 2001 and 2006, reductions in state general funds and state motor vehicle sales tax collections forced a set of service cuts, fare increases and fuel surcharges, all of which reduced ridership.\n\nLocal policy requires that one third of the system's funding is to come from [[fare]]s and current operations slightly exceed that level. Since 1 October 2008, fares on all buses and trains increased by 25 cents.<ref>http://www.metrotransit.org/news/stories/09_08_fareincrease.asp</ref> Express routes cost more (on limited-stop portions) and certain eligible individuals (such as riders with disabilities) may ride for $1. Many of the fares are more expensive during [[rush hour]] periods. For instance, a rush-hour ride on an express bus costs $3.25, as opposed to $2.50 for non-rush hours. \n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metrotransit.org/fares |website=Metro Transit}}</ref>\n\nThe system does not make much use of fare zones aside from downtown zones in Minneapolis and St. Paul, where rides only cost $0.50. [[Transfer (public transit)|Fare transfer]] cards valid for 2.5 hours are available upon payment of fare. Only the Northstar commuter rail line charges fares based on distance. A number of discounted multiple-use transit pass options are available. In early 2007, the system introduced a [[contactless smart card]] (the [[Go-To card]]) for paying fares.\n\nA second fare increase occurred in 2017. \"Under the new system, local fares for off-peak hours will increase from $1.75 to $2; while rides will go from $2.25 to $2.50 for peak hours. Metro Mobility users will pay $3.50 to $4.50 per ride, as well as an additional 75-cent surcharge for trips greater than 15 miles. Transit Link Dial-A-Ride fares will increase, on average, by $1.60, and include a 75-cent distance surcharge.\"<ref name=\"Star Tribune\">{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Janet |title=Met Council votes to increase transit fares by 25 cents |url=http://www.startribune.com/it-s-official-transit-fare-increase-of-25-cents/436833953/ |accessdate=July 27, 2017 |publisher=Star Tribune |date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Metro Light Rail and Bus Rapid Transit==\n{{main|Metro (Minnesota)}}\n'''Metro''' is the system of color-coded light rail and bus rapid transit lines owned by the Metropolitan Council that provide service to the Twin Cities region. Metro Transit is the operator of both of the region's light rail lines: the Metro Blue Line and the Metro Green Line. Service on the Metro Red Line bus rapid transit line is operated by [[Minnesota Valley Transit Authority]].\n\n===Metro Blue Line===\n{{main|Blue Line (Minnesota)}}\n[[File:Blue Line Light Rail Train.jpg|thumb|A southbound train from the [[46th Street (Metro Transit station)|46th Street Station]].]]\n[[File:Minneapolis Light Train.jpg|thumb|Light rail in downtown Minneapolis.]]\nThe Metro Blue Line (route 55) opened on June 26, 2004, providing service between [[Hennepin Avenue|Hennepin Ave.]]/[[North Loop, Minneapolis|Warehouse District]] Station and [[Fort Snelling (Metro Transit station)|Fort Snelling]] Station. On December 4, 2004, service was extended to [[Mall of America]] Station via [[Minneapolis\u2013St. Paul International Airport]]. As part of the [[Northstar Commuter Rail]] project, on November 14, 2009, the Blue Line was extended a few blocks north to [[Target Field (Metro Transit Station)]] to provide connections to the new commuter rail line. Current construction plans call for a northern extension of the Metro Blue Line to [[Brooklyn Park, Minnesota|Brooklyn Park]], the current opening date is in the air as BNSF is unwilling to work with Metro Transit on co-locating freight rail and light rail.\n\n===Metro Green Line===\n{{main|Metro Green Line (Minnesota)}}\nThe Metro Green Line opened on June 14, 2014 and connects Downtown Minneapolis, the [[University of Minnesota]], the Midway and Saint Anthony Park neighborhoods of St. Paul, the State Capitol and Downtown St. Paul with light rail service. Future plans call for extending the Green Line to [[Eden Prairie, Minnesota|Eden Prairie]] via the job-rich southwestern suburbs. The Southwest extension isn't expected to be operational until 2023.\n\n===Metro Red Line===\n{{main|Metro Red Line (Minnesota)}}\nThe Metro Red Line is a bus rapid transit line operated by Minnesota Valley Transit Authority on behalf of the Metropolitan Council, providing connections between the Blue Line at Mall of America and the southern suburb of [[Apple Valley, Minnesota|Apple Valley]]. Service began on June 22, 2013.\n\n===Metro Orange Line===\n{{main|Metro Orange Line (Minnesota)}}\nThe Metro Orange Line is a bus rapid transit line that will operate along [[Interstate 35W (Minnesota)|Interstate 35W]] from Downtown Minneapolis to the southern suburbs, terminating in [[Burnsville, Minnesota|Burnsville]]. Recent estimates anticipate opening the Orange Line in 2021.\n\n==Bus routes==\n\n{{main|Metro Transit Routes}}\n\n[[File:SaintPaul 2012 MetroTransit bus-stop.jpg|thumb|An old Metro Transit bus stop sign in downtown Saint Paul, showing all the routes that stop at this location. Newer, more detailed bus stop signs are being gradually introduced.]]\n\nMetro Transit operates 123 bus routes, 66 of which are local routes and 51 are express routes. An additional six bus routes are operated under contract with [[Maple Grove Transit]]. In 2012, Metro Transit buses averaged 230,575 riders per weekday. The system operates almost 900 [[Bus stop|wait shelters]], including 180 reclaimed from CBS Outdoor in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/minneapolis/245071671.html |title=As big cities privatize bus shelters, Minneapolis moves them to government control |accessdate=2014-05-04 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407194105/http://www.startribune.com/local/minneapolis/245071671.html |archivedate=April 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nBus routes are numbered in accordance to portions of the metropolitan area served. Bus routes that primarily serve Minneapolis are numbered 1\u201349, 50\u201359 are inner-city limited-stop routes, 60\u201389 primarily serve St. Paul, and route 94 is an express route that connects the core areas of Minneapolis and St. Paul via [[Interstate 94 in Minnesota|I-94]]. 100 series routes are primarily commuter routes connecting outlying neighborhoods of Minneapolis and St. Paul to the cities' cores, as well as the University of Minnesota. 200 series routes serve the northeast metro, 300 series the southeast, 400 series the southern [[Dakota County, Minnesota|Dakota]] and [[Scott County, Minnesota|Scott County]] suburbs, 500 series the suburbs of [[Richfield, Minnesota|Richfield]], [[Edina, Minnesota|Edina]], and [[Bloomington, Minnesota|Bloomington]], 600 series the west and southwest metro, 700 series the northwest metro and 800 series northern [[Anoka County, Minnesota|Anoka County]] suburbs.\n\nThree-digit route numbers are further subdivided into two groups. Routes ending in x00\u2013x49 are typically local service bus routes connecting METRO stations, shopping areas and other local destinations, whereas those ending in x50\u2013x99 are primarily express service routes which connect outlying suburbs and park and ride facilities to the [[Central business district#United States|central business districts]] of Minneapolis and St. Paul. Additionally, the Northstar Commuter Rail line is publicly given route number 888.\n\n===Hi-Frequency Network===\n\nA subset of the bus network, known as the '''Hi-Frequency Network''' was created on September 9, 2006. This network highlights fourteen bus routes that offer service every 15 minutes or better on weekday periods from 6 am to 7 pm and on Saturdays from 9 am to 6 pm. Segments of routes 2, 5, 6, 10, 11, 18, 21, 64, 54, 515, and all of METRO A Line, [[C Line (Minnesota)|C Line]], Blue Line, and Green Line are currently part of the Hi-Frequency Network.<ref>{{cite web |title=High Frequency network |url=https://www.metrotransit.org/high-frequency-network |website=www.metrotransit.org |accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Arterial Bus Rapid Transit===\n\nMetro Transit has been investing into what it refers to as the [https://www.metrotransit.org/abrt Arterial Bus Rapid Transit] network or \"ABRT\", an enhanced bus service featuring improved station facilities and vehicles, off-board fare payment for reduced dwell-time, higher frequency, and greater spacing between stops for reduced travel time. Currently, planned and existing ABRT lines do not feature exclusive bus lanes. ABRT is also variably referred to as \"Rapid Bus\" or \"Arterial Transit\", among others.\n\nMetro Transit built the [http://www.metrotransit.org/a-line-project A-Line], [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]]'s first arterial [[bus rapid transit]] line, along [[Snelling Avenue]] and Ford Parkway.  The [[Metro A Line (Minnesota)|A Line]] connects the [[Metro Blue Line (Minnesota)|Metro Blue Line]] at 46th St. Station to [[Rosedale Center]] with a connection at the [[Metro Green Line (Minnesota)|Metro Green Line]] [[Snelling Avenue (Metro Transit station)|Snelling Avenue station]].  The A-Line is the first in a series of planned arterial bus rapid transit lines. The A Line opened on June 11, 2016.<ref>http://www.metrotransit.org/a-line-project A-Line</ref>\n\nThe B line is an arterial bus rapid transit route proposed for the Twin Cities' Lake Street/Marshall Avenue corridor, running from [[Bde Maka Ska]] in Minneapolis' Uptown neighborhood to the Snelling Avenue station of the Green Line,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/b-line-project|title=METRO B Line (Lake Street / Marshall Avenue)|access-date=May 24, 2019}}</ref> with a possible extension to downtown [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.twincities.com/2019/05/06/st-paul-chamber-mayor-join-call-for-new-b-line-bus-to-extend-to-downtown-st-paul/|title=St. Paul chamber, mayor call for new B Line bus to extend to downtown St. Paul|access-date=May 24, 2019}}</ref>  Planning is underway and will continue through early 2020. Station design is planned for 2020-2021 with beginning of construction anticipated in 2022, pending full funding.\n\nThe [[C Line (Minnesota)|C Line]] is an arterial bus rapid transit route that  began revenue service on June 8, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/c-line-project|title=C Line Project - Metro Transit|website=www.metrotransit.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/construction-officially-begins-on-c-line-rapid-bus/477414233/|title=Construction officially begins on C-Line rapid bus|work=Star Tribune|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref> It runs from downtown Minneapolis to the Brooklyn Center Transit Center.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/c-line-project|title=C Line (Penn Avenue rapid bus)|access-date=May 24, 2019}}</ref>  \n\nThe [[D Line (Minnesota)|D Line]] is an arterial bus rapid transit route currently in planning stages. The route plan runs from Brooklyn Center through Downtown Minneapolis and onward through south [[Minneapolis]] to the [[Mall of America station|Mall of America]] Station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/d-line-project|title=D Line (Chicago-Fremont rapid bus)|access-date=May 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe E line is an arterial bus rapid transit route proposed for the Twin Cities' Hennepin Avenue corridor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/e-line-project|title=E Line (Hennepin Avenue rapid bus project)|access-date=May 24, 2019}}</ref>  Metro Transit's 2012 rapid bus study identified a route that would run from downtown [[Minneapolis]] to a future Lake Street station on the [[Metro Green Line (Minnesota)|METRO Green Line]] extension.  However, Metro Transit is studying the corridor again to determine the need for a longer route.  Following the corridor study, E Line station planning will begin in 2019. Pending full project funding, E Line construction could begin as soon as 2023.\n\n==Northstar Line==\n{{main|Northstar Line}}\nThe Northstar Line is a commuter rail line providing service between Minneapolis and [[Big Lake, Minnesota]], which opened on November 16, 2009. There are additional bus connections to [[Becker, Minnesota|Becker]] and [[St. Cloud, Minnesota|St. Cloud]], with five round-trips in the peak direction, one reverse commute round-trip on weekdays, and three round-trips on Saturdays and Sundays. Additional service is provided on event days, such as during [[Minnesota Twins|Twins]] and [[Minnesota Vikings|Vikings]] games or the [[Super Bowl]].  However, service is not provided on holidays.\n\n==Facilities==\n[[Image:Metro Transit-seat-20081002.JPG|thumb|Metro Transit symbol on a seat on a new bus on [[University Avenue (Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul)|University Avenue]]]]\n\n===Nicollet Mall===\n\n[[Nicollet Mall]] had been used exclusively for buses and taxis for many years, but the number of buses is being reduced to allow more bicycle use of Nicollet. Beginning in 2005, Metro Transit and the city of Minneapolis experimented with diverting buses from Nicollet to Hennepin Avenue in the evening hours to reduce noise. In December 2009, the \u201cMARQ2\u201d project, partly funded by the federal government under the [[Urban Partnership Agreement]], was completed, in which two-lane busways were built along the parallel roads of Marquette and 2nd Avenue South.<ref name=\"mt-marq2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrotransit.org/marq2/|title=Faster express service is coming to downtown Minneapolis|publisher=Metro Transit|accessdate=December 16, 2009}}</ref> A system of lettered gates was established, by which buses would only stop every other block along those two one-mile corridors.  NexTrip digital signs with arrival times were also added, although they weren't functioning at the beginning of the rollout. NexTrip information has also been available through the Metro Transit website since 2008 and can be accessed with [[mobile web browser]]s.<ref name=\"nextrip-may08\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrocouncil.org/directions/transit/transit2008/NexTripMay08.htm|title=Exactly when is my next bus departing?|date=May 14, 2009|publisher=Metropolitan Council|accessdate=December 17, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516055453/http://www.metrocouncil.org/directions/transit/transit2008/NexTripMay08.htm|archivedate=May 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Bus-only shoulders===\n\nSince 1991, Metro Transit buses have been allowed to use \u201c[[Bus bypass shoulder|bus-only shoulders]],\u201d road shoulders to bypass [[traffic jams]]. Currently, buses are allowed to travel no more than {{convert|35|mph|abbr=on}} or {{convert|15|mph|abbr=on}} faster than the congested traffic in the general purpose lanes. Bus drivers must be very attentive when taking the bus onto the shoulder, since that part of the road is only about one foot wider than the buses in many cases. To help with this issue, researchers at the University of Minnesota helped rig up a bus with a [[lane-keep system]], along with a [[heads-up display]] connected to a [[radar]] system to alert the driver of any obstacles. The technology was an adaptation of a system previously tested with drivers of [[snowplow]]s and made some headlines in the early 2000s. This system will be more widely deployed under the Urban Partnership Agreement that assisted in the Marq2 project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upa.dot.gov/agreements/minneapolis.htm |title=Minneapolis Urban Partnership Agreement |work=Urban Partnership Agreement and Congestion Reduction Demonstration Programs |publisher=U.S. Department of Transportation |accessdate=2010-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100827130236/http://www.upa.dot.gov/agreements/minneapolis.htm |archivedate=2010-08-27 }}</ref>\n\n===Transit centers===\n\nMetro Transit operates service to 28 [[transit center]]s, which provide connection points for bus and rail service throughout the metropolitan area.\n\n===Park and rides===\n\nMetro Transit operates service to 79 [[park and ride]] lots and ramps, with a total of 13,829 parking spaces. These lots allow commuters to park their cars for free and take buses and trains to the downtown areas to avoid traffic congestion and parking fees.\n\n== Fleet ==\n=== Buses ===\n[[File:Metro Transit bus stop at Coffman Memorial Union.jpg|thumb|Metro Transit buses at Washington Avenue bus stop on north side of [[Coffman Memorial Union]] on the [[University of Minnesota]] East Bank campus.]]\nMetro Transit operates the [[Gillig Phantom]], [[Gillig Low Floor|Gillig Advantage]] (which comprises the majority of the fleet), [[New Flyer]] D60HF, D60LFR, Xcelsior XD60, and [[Motor Coach Industries|MCI]] D4500.\n\nIn the 2000s, most buses had a mostly white [[livery]] with a predominantly blue strip running horizontally along the side and a large white \u201cT\u201d inside a red circle on the roof. Diesel\u2013electric hybrid buses introduced toward the end of the decade spurred new color schemes, with yellow at the front and the blue line moved above the side windows. The METRO light-rail vehicles have a different color scheme: predominantly blue and white, with yellow on each end. Metro Transit also uses [[vehicle wrap]] advertising on some buses and light rail cars, creating a different appearance.\n\nAll of the buses are [[handicapped-accessible]], either using [[hydraulic]] lifts or a [[low-floor]] design. The Metropolitan Council also operates the Metro Mobility [[paratransit]] system for door-to-door transportation.\n\nAll Metro Transit buses and light- and heavy-rail trains have bike racks installed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metrotransit.org/bike-options.aspx |title=Metro Transit - Bike Options}}</ref>\n\n=== Rail ===\n{{main|Metro Transit rolling stock}}\n\n[[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]] [[Flexity Swift]] 27 vehicles are operated on the [[Blue Line (Minnesota)|Blue Line]] light rail line. There are also 59 [[Siemens S70]] vehicles operating on both the Blue and [[Green Line (Minnesota)|Green Line]] light rail lines.<ref>{{cite web|title=Central Corridor Contracts Awarded|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/stpaul/101524299.html|accessdate=20 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829080932/http://www.startribune.com/local/stpaul/101524299.html|archivedate=29 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FTA Signs Agreement to Fund Central Corridor|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/index.php?id=44&no_cache=1&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=13180&cHash=00d875d42e|accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref> Rolling stock for the [[Northstar Line]] commuter rail line consists of [[Bombardier BiLevel Coach]]es pulled by [[MotivePower Industries|MotivePower]] [[MPI MPXpress|MP36]] locomotives.\n\n==See also==\n\nOpt-out and regional providers:\n*[[Maple Grove Transit]]\n*[[Minnesota Valley Transit Authority]]\n*[[Plymouth Metrolink]]\n*[[SouthWest Transit]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.metrotransit.org/ Metro Transit]\n* [http://www.metrotransit.org/transit-police Metro Transit Police]\n* [https://www.metrotransit.org/system-map System map]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060929134020/http://www.metrocouncil.org/planning/transportation/transportation.htm Report on the Twin Cities Transit System]\n* {{cite news \n| url         = https://www.forbes.com/sites/michelinemaynard/2013/06/26/streetcars-are-rolling-all-over-as-minneapolis-jumps-on-board/\n| title       = Streetcars Are Rolling All Over, As Minneapolis Jumps On Board\n| publisher   = [[Forbes magazine]]\n| author      = Micheline Maynard\n| date        = 2013-06-26\n| accessdate  = 2013-06-27\n| quote       = The Twin City got permission from the state legislature to redirect about $60 million in property taxes to pay for part of the $200 million project.\n}}\n\n{{Twin Cities Transit}}\n\n[[Category:Bus transportation in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Light rail in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Paratransit services in the United States]]\n[[Category:Intermodal transportation authorities in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Commuter rail in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Bus rapid transit in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other systems of the same name|Metro Transit (disambiguation)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=May 2008}}\n\n{{Infobox bus transit\n| name            = Metro Transit\n| logo            = Metro Transit logo.svg\n| logo_size       = 250\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_caption   = Metro Transit operates public transit in four different modes in the Minneapolis\u2013St. Paul area.\n| parent          = [[Metropolitan Council]]\n| founded         = 1967\n| headquarters    = [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]], United States\n| locale          = [[Minneapolis \u2013 Saint Paul]]\n| service_type    = [[Transit bus]]<br/>[[Bus rapid transit]]<br/>[[Light rail]]<br/>[[Commuter rail]]<br/>[[Paratransit]]\n| routes          = 127 bus<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/metro-transit-facts|title=Metro Transit 2017 Facts|publisher=Metro Transit|accessdate=March 22, 2018}}</ref><br/>2 bus rapid transit<br/>2 light rail<br/>1 commuter rail\n| fleet           = 514 diesel buses<br/>133 hybrid-electric buses<br/>13 rapid buses<br/>64 coach buses<br/>185 Articulated buses<br/>91 light rail vehicles<br/>6 locomotives<br/>18 rail coaches\n| ridership       = 260,486 (2018)<ref name=\"apta-stats\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/metro-transit-facts|title=Metro Transit 2017 Facts|publisher=Metro Transit|accessdate=September 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| leader_type     = General Manager\n| operator        = Metro Transit\n| leader          = Wes Kooistra\n| website         = http://www.metrotransit.org/\n}}\n\n'''Metro Transit''' is the primary [[public transportation]] operator in the [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]] area of the U.S. state of [[Minnesota]] and the largest operator in the state. The system is a division of the [[Metropolitan Council]], the region's [[metropolitan planning organization]] (MPO), averaging 264,347 riders each weekday, carrying 90% to 95% of the transit riders in the region on a combined network of regular-route [[bus]]es, [[light rail]] and [[commuter rail]].<ref name=\"about\"/> The remainder of Twin Cities transit ridership is generally split among suburban \u201copt-out\u201d carriers operating out of cities that have chosen not to participate in the Metro Transit network. The biggest opt-out providers are [[Minnesota Valley Transit Authority]] (MVTA), [[Maple Grove Transit]] and [[Southwest Transit]] (SW Transit). The [[University of Minnesota]] also operates a [[University of Minnesota Campus Shuttle|campus shuttle system]] that coordinates routes with Metro Transit services.\n\nIn 2017, buses carried about 68% of the system's passengers. Just above 16% of ridership was concentrated on Metro Transit's busiest route, the [[Green Line (Minnesota)|Green Line]] light rail. The region's other light rail line, the [[Blue Line (Minnesota)|Blue Line]], fell close behind, carrying 13% of Metro Transit passengers. Nearly 2% rode the [[A Line (Minnesota)|A Line]] arterial rapid bus line. The remaining approximately 1% rode the [[Northstar Commuter Rail]] service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/rail-lines-set-records-as-metro-transit-ridership-tops-819-million-in-2017|title=Rail lines set records as Metro Transit ridership tops 81.9 million in 2017 - Metro Transit|website=www.metrotransit.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> In 2015, Metro Transit saw its highest yearly ridership ever, with a total of 85.8 million trips, 62.1 million (72%) of which were on buses. The remaining 23.7 million (28%) of passengers traveled on the region's rail lines, including the recently opened [[Green Line (Minnesota)|Green Line]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/Data/Sites/1/media/about/facts/2015/2015_metrotransit_facts.pdf|title=2015 Metro Transit Facts|access-date=May 10, 2018}}</ref> The single-day ridership record is 369,626, set on September 1, 2016.<ref>{{cite news | newspaper = [[Star Tribune]] | url = http://www.startribune.com/vikings-twins-traffic-fears-help-metro-transit-shatter-single-day-ridership-record/392920421/ | title = Vikings, Twins, traffic fears help Metro Transit shatter single-day ridership record | last = Harlow | first = Tim | date = September 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nMetro Transit drivers and vehicle maintenance personnel are organized through the [[Amalgamated Transit Union]]. The agency also contracts with private providers such as [[First Transit]] to offer paratansit services which operate under the Metro Mobility brand.\n\n==History==\nThe agency was established by the [[Minnesota State Legislature]] in 1967 as the '''Metropolitan Transit Commission''' ('''MTC''').<ref>Christopher, Mary Kay. Bus Transit Service in Land Development Planning. Transportation Research Board, 2006.</ref> MTC's operations were moved under the auspices of the [[Metropolitan Council]] in 1994, prompting a name change to \u201cMetropolitan Council Transit Operations\u201d and then, in 1998, to Metro Transit. The organization traces its history back to the 19th-century [[streetcar]] systems of the region through the acquisition in 1970 of the [[Twin City Rapid Transit|Twin City Lines]] bus system from businessman [[Carl Pohlad]]. At the time of the acquisition, Twin City Lines had 635 buses: 75% of those were over 15 years old and 86 buses were so old that they were banned from operating in Minneapolis. MTC acquired 465 new buses over the next five years and built many new bus shelters.<ref name=\"met-council-40\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrocouncil.org/about/metcouncilhistory.pdf|title=A bold experiment: the Metropolitan Council at 40|publisher=Metropolitan Council|accessdate=December 16, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613070633/http://metrocouncil.org/about/MetCouncilHistory.pdf|archivedate=June 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\nShortly thereafter, a long battle began to return rail transit to the region and efforts for additional lines continue at a snail's pace. It took 32 years to see the first line implemented. In 1972, the Regional Fixed Guideway Study for MTC proposed a $1.3 billion 37- or 57-mile (sources differ) [[Heavy rail#Heavy rail|heavy-rail]] [[rapid transit]] system, but the then-separate Metropolitan Council disagreed with that idea\u2014refusing to even look at the plan\u2014and continuing political battles prevented its implementation. The Met Council had its own plans for [[bus rapid transit]] in the Cities. Another system using smaller [[people mover]]s was proposed in the 1975 Small Vehicle Fixed Guideway Study and gained the most traction with the [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]] city council, but was eventually dropped in 1980. In the 1980s, [[light rail]] was proposed as an alternative and several possible corridors were identified, including the [[Green Line (Minnesota)|Central Corridor]], for which a draft [[environmental impact statement]] (DEIS) was drawn up in 1982.<ref name=\"met-council-40\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.citypages.com/blotter/2008/05/a_train_between.php|title=A train linking Minneapolis and St. Paul? We had that scoop in 1984|work=City Pages|author=Jeff Severns Guntzel|date=May 19, 2008|accessdate=2010-02-17|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100217082303/http://blogs.citypages.com/blotter/2008/05/a_train_between.php|archivedate=February 17, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=ALL ABOARD: For the Transit Study that Never Ends|work=City Pages|date=September 5, 1984}}</ref> However, it was another two decades before the [[Blue Line (Minnesota)|Blue Line]] light rail line began operation on June 26, 2004, by then, just over 50 years since the last regular-service streetcar ran on June 19, 1954, under the old Twin City Lines. Heavy-rail commuter service began on November 14, 2009, with the [[Northstar Line]]. The 2010s decade may finally see several new lines open.\n\n[[Image:Metro Transit-University Avenue-20081002.JPG|thumb|left|upright|Bus and driver on University Avenue in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]], near Saint Paul]]\nMetro Transit does not cover the whole Twin Cities area. Bus service in the suburbs was being cut back in the early 1980s and suburb-to-suburb service was limited (an issue that remains today). In 1986, cities and counties in the seven-county metropolitan area were given the option to run their own bus services and leave the MTC system. About 17.5% of the area which has regular route transit service is served by these six other \u201copt out\u201d transit systems. About 5% of the system is contracted to private transit providers.\n\nIn the mid-2000s decade, the system claimed to have a safety record five times better than the national average.\n\n==Funding==\nMetro Transit currently receives the majority of its funding from the State Motor Vehicle Sales Tax, the State General Fund, fares and federal revenues. Metro Transit prepares an annual calendar budget, but most of its [[subsidy]] comes from state funds, on a July 1 biennial budget. Between 2001 and 2006, reductions in state general funds and state motor vehicle sales tax collections forced a set of service cuts, fare increases and fuel surcharges, all of which reduced ridership.\n\nLocal policy requires that one third of the system's funding is to come from [[fare]]s and current operations slightly exceed that level. Since 1 October 2008, fares on all buses and trains increased by 25 cents.<ref>http://www.metrotransit.org/news/stories/09_08_fareincrease.asp</ref> Express routes cost more (on limited-stop portions) and certain eligible individuals (such as riders with disabilities) may ride for $1. Many of the fares are more expensive during [[rush hour]] periods. For instance, a rush-hour ride on an express bus costs $3.25, as opposed to $2.50 for non-rush hours. \n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metrotransit.org/fares |website=Metro Transit}}</ref>\n\nThe system does not make much use of fare zones aside from downtown zones in Minneapolis and St. Paul, where rides only cost $0.50. [[Transfer (public transit)|Fare transfer]] cards valid for 2.5 hours are available upon payment of fare. Only the Northstar commuter rail line charges fares based on distance. A number of discounted multiple-use transit pass options are available. In early 2007, the system introduced a [[contactless smart card]] (the [[Go-To card]]) for paying fares.\n\nA second fare increase occurred in 2017. \"Under the new system, local fares for off-peak hours will increase from $1.75 to $2; while rides will go from $2.25 to $2.50 for peak hours. Metro Mobility users will pay $3.50 to $4.50 per ride, as well as an additional 75-cent surcharge for trips greater than 15 miles. Transit Link Dial-A-Ride fares will increase, on average, by $1.60, and include a 75-cent distance surcharge.\"<ref name=\"Star Tribune\">{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Janet |title=Met Council votes to increase transit fares by 25 cents |url=http://www.startribune.com/it-s-official-transit-fare-increase-of-25-cents/436833953/ |accessdate=July 27, 2017 |publisher=Star Tribune |date=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Metro Light Rail and Bus Rapid Transit==\n{{main|Metro (Minnesota)}}\n'''Metro''' is the system of color-coded light rail and bus rapid transit lines owned by the Metropolitan Council that provide service to the Twin Cities region. Metro Transit is the operator of both of the region's light rail lines: the Metro Blue Line and the Metro Green Line. Service on the Metro Red Line bus rapid transit line is operated by [[Minnesota Valley Transit Authority]].\n\n===Metro Blue Line===\n{{main|Blue Line (Minnesota)}}\n[[File:Blue Line Light Rail Train.jpg|thumb|A southbound train from the [[46th Street (Metro Transit station)|46th Street Station]].]]\n[[File:Minneapolis Light Train.jpg|thumb|Light rail in downtown Minneapolis.]]\nThe Metro Blue Line (route 55) opened on June 26, 2004, providing service between [[Hennepin Avenue|Hennepin Ave.]]/[[North Loop, Minneapolis|Warehouse District]] Station and [[Fort Snelling (Metro Transit station)|Fort Snelling]] Station. On December 4, 2004, service was extended to [[Mall of America]] Station via [[Minneapolis\u2013St. Paul International Airport]]. As part of the [[Northstar Commuter Rail]] project, on November 14, 2009, the Blue Line was extended a few blocks north to [[Target Field (Metro Transit Station)]] to provide connections to the new commuter rail line. Current construction plans call for a northern extension of the Metro Blue Line to [[Brooklyn Park, Minnesota|Brooklyn Park]], the current opening date is in the air as BNSF is unwilling to work with Metro Transit on co-locating freight rail and light rail.\n\n===Metro Green Line===\n{{main|Metro Green Line (Minnesota)}}\nThe Metro Green Line opened on June 14, 2014 and connects Downtown Minneapolis, the [[University of Minnesota]], the Midway and Saint Anthony Park neighborhoods of St. Paul, the State Capitol and Downtown St. Paul with light rail service. Future plans call for extending the Green Line to [[Eden Prairie, Minnesota|Eden Prairie]] via the job-rich southwestern suburbs. The Southwest extension isn't expected to be operational until 2023.\n\n===Metro Red Line===\n{{main|Metro Red Line (Minnesota)}}\nThe Metro Red Line is a bus rapid transit line operated by Minnesota Valley Transit Authority on behalf of the Metropolitan Council, providing connections between the Blue Line at Mall of America and the southern suburb of [[Apple Valley, Minnesota|Apple Valley]]. Service began on June 22, 2013.\n\n===Metro Orange Line===\n{{main|Metro Orange Line (Minnesota)}}\nThe Metro Orange Line is a bus rapid transit line that will operate along [[Interstate 35W (Minnesota)|Interstate 35W]] from Downtown Minneapolis to the southern suburbs, terminating in [[Burnsville, Minnesota|Burnsville]]. Recent estimates anticipate opening the Orange Line in 2021.\n\n==Bus routes==\n\n{{main|Metro Transit Routes}}\n\n[[File:SaintPaul 2012 MetroTransit bus-stop.jpg|thumb|An old Metro Transit bus stop sign in downtown Saint Paul, showing all the routes that stop at this location. Newer, more detailed bus stop signs are being gradually introduced.]]\n\nMetro Transit operates 123 bus routes, 66 of which are local routes and 51 are express routes. An additional six bus routes are operated under contract with [[Maple Grove Transit]]. In 2012, Metro Transit buses averaged 230,575 riders per weekday. The system operates almost 900 [[Bus stop|wait shelters]], including 180 reclaimed from CBS Outdoor in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/minneapolis/245071671.html |title=As big cities privatize bus shelters, Minneapolis moves them to government control |accessdate=2014-05-04 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407194105/http://www.startribune.com/local/minneapolis/245071671.html |archivedate=April 7, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nBus routes are numbered in accordance to portions of the metropolitan area served. Bus routes that primarily serve Minneapolis are numbered 1\u201349, 50\u201359 are inner-city limited-stop routes, 60\u201389 primarily serve St. Paul, and route 94 is an express route that connects the core areas of Minneapolis and St. Paul via [[Interstate 94 in Minnesota|I-94]]. 100 series routes are primarily commuter routes connecting outlying neighborhoods of Minneapolis and St. Paul to the cities' cores, as well as the University of Minnesota. 200 series routes serve the northeast metro, 300 series the southeast, 400 series the southern [[Dakota County, Minnesota|Dakota]] and [[Scott County, Minnesota|Scott County]] suburbs, 500 series the suburbs of [[Richfield, Minnesota|Richfield]], [[Edina, Minnesota|Edina]], and [[Bloomington, Minnesota|Bloomington]], 600 series the west and southwest metro, 700 series the northwest metro and 800 series northern [[Anoka County, Minnesota|Anoka County]] suburbs.\n\nThree-digit route numbers are further subdivided into two groups. Routes ending in x00\u2013x49 are typically local service bus routes connecting METRO stations, shopping areas and other local destinations, whereas those ending in x50\u2013x99 are primarily express service routes which connect outlying suburbs and park and ride facilities to the [[Central business district#United States|central business districts]] of Minneapolis and St. Paul. Additionally, the Northstar Commuter Rail line is publicly given route number 888.\n\n===Hi-Frequency Network===\n\nA subset of the bus network, known as the '''Hi-Frequency Network''' was created on September 9, 2006. This network highlights fourteen bus routes that offer service every 15 minutes or better on weekday periods from 6 am to 7 pm and on Saturdays from 9 am to 6 pm. Segments of routes 2, 5, 6, 10, 11, 18, 21, 64, 54, 515, and all of METRO A Line, [[C Line (Minnesota)|C Line]], Blue Line, and Green Line are currently part of the Hi-Frequency Network.<ref>{{cite web |title=High Frequency network |url=https://www.metrotransit.org/high-frequency-network |website=www.metrotransit.org |accessdate=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Arterial Bus Rapid Transit===\n\nMetro Transit has been investing into what it refers to as the [https://www.metrotransit.org/abrt Arterial Bus Rapid Transit] network or \"ABRT\", an enhanced bus service featuring improved station facilities and vehicles, off-board fare payment for reduced dwell-time, higher frequency, and greater spacing between stops for reduced travel time. Currently, planned and existing ABRT lines do not feature exclusive bus lanes. ABRT is also variably referred to as \"Rapid Bus\" or \"Arterial Transit\", among others.\n\nMetro Transit built the [http://www.metrotransit.org/a-line-project A-Line], [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]]'s first arterial [[bus rapid transit]] line, along [[Snelling Avenue]] and Ford Parkway.  The [[Metro A Line (Minnesota)|A Line]] connects the [[Metro Blue Line (Minnesota)|Metro Blue Line]] at 46th St. Station to [[Rosedale Center]] with a connection at the [[Metro Green Line (Minnesota)|Metro Green Line]] [[Snelling Avenue (Metro Transit station)|Snelling Avenue station]].  The A-Line is the first in a series of planned arterial bus rapid transit lines. The A Line opened on June 11, 2016.<ref>http://www.metrotransit.org/a-line-project A-Line</ref>\n\nThe B line is an arterial bus rapid transit route proposed for the Twin Cities' Lake Street/Marshall Avenue corridor, running from [[Bde Maka Ska]] in Minneapolis' Uptown neighborhood to the Snelling Avenue station of the Green Line,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/b-line-project|title=METRO B Line (Lake Street / Marshall Avenue)|access-date=May 24, 2019}}</ref> with a possible extension to downtown [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.twincities.com/2019/05/06/st-paul-chamber-mayor-join-call-for-new-b-line-bus-to-extend-to-downtown-st-paul/|title=St. Paul chamber, mayor call for new B Line bus to extend to downtown St. Paul|access-date=May 24, 2019}}</ref>  Planning is underway and will continue through early 2020. Station design is planned for 2020-2021 with beginning of construction anticipated in 2022, pending full funding.\n\nThe [[C Line (Minnesota)|C Line]] is an arterial bus rapid transit route that  began revenue service on June 8, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/c-line-project|title=C Line Project - Metro Transit|website=www.metrotransit.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/construction-officially-begins-on-c-line-rapid-bus/477414233/|title=Construction officially begins on C-Line rapid bus|work=Star Tribune|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref> It runs from downtown Minneapolis to the Brooklyn Center Transit Center.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/c-line-project|title=C Line (Penn Avenue rapid bus)|access-date=May 24, 2019}}</ref>  \n\nThe [[D Line (Minnesota)|D Line]] is an arterial bus rapid transit route currently in planning stages. The route plan runs from Brooklyn Center through Downtown Minneapolis and onward through south [[Minneapolis]] to the [[Mall of America station|Mall of America]] Station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/d-line-project|title=D Line (Chicago-Fremont rapid bus)|access-date=May 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe E line is an arterial bus rapid transit route proposed for the Twin Cities' Hennepin Avenue corridor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/e-line-project|title=E Line (Hennepin Avenue rapid bus project)|access-date=May 24, 2019}}</ref>  Metro Transit's 2012 rapid bus study identified a route that would run from downtown [[Minneapolis]] to a future Lake Street station on the [[Metro Green Line (Minnesota)|METRO Green Line]] extension.  However, Metro Transit is studying the corridor again to determine the need for a longer route.  Following the corridor study, E Line station planning will begin in 2019. Pending full project funding, E Line construction could begin as soon as 2023.\n\n==Northstar Line==\n{{main|Northstar Line}}\nThe Northstar Line is a commuter rail line providing service between Minneapolis and [[Big Lake, Minnesota]], which opened on November 16, 2009. There are additional bus connections to [[Becker, Minnesota|Becker]] and [[St. Cloud, Minnesota|St. Cloud]], with five round-trips in the peak direction, one reverse commute round-trip on weekdays, and three round-trips on Saturdays and Sundays. Additional service is provided on event days, such as during [[Minnesota Twins|Twins]] and [[Minnesota Vikings|Vikings]] games or the [[Super Bowl]].  However, service is not provided on holidays.\n\n==Facilities==\n[[Image:Metro Transit-seat-20081002.JPG|thumb|Metro Transit symbol on a seat on a new bus on [[University Avenue (Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul)|University Avenue]]]]\n\n===Nicollet Mall===\n\n[[Nicollet Mall]] had been used exclusively for buses and taxis for many years, but the number of buses is being reduced to allow more bicycle use of Nicollet. Beginning in 2005, Metro Transit and the city of Minneapolis experimented with diverting buses from Nicollet to Hennepin Avenue in the evening hours to reduce noise. In December 2009, the \u201cMARQ2\u201d project, partly funded by the federal government under the [[Urban Partnership Agreement]], was completed, in which two-lane busways were built along the parallel roads of Marquette and 2nd Avenue South.<ref name=\"mt-marq2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrotransit.org/marq2/|title=Faster express service is coming to downtown Minneapolis|publisher=Metro Transit|accessdate=December 16, 2009}}</ref> A system of lettered gates was established, by which buses would only stop every other block along those two one-mile corridors.  NexTrip digital signs with arrival times were also added, although they weren't functioning at the beginning of the rollout. NexTrip information has also been available through the Metro Transit website since 2008 and can be accessed with [[mobile web browser]]s.<ref name=\"nextrip-may08\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrocouncil.org/directions/transit/transit2008/NexTripMay08.htm|title=Exactly when is my next bus departing?|date=May 14, 2009|publisher=Metropolitan Council|accessdate=December 17, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516055453/http://www.metrocouncil.org/directions/transit/transit2008/NexTripMay08.htm|archivedate=May 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Bus-only shoulders===\n\nSince 1991, Metro Transit buses have been allowed to use \u201cbus-only shoulders,\u201d [[road shoulder]]s to bypass [[traffic jams]]. Currently, buses are allowed to travel no more than {{convert|35|mph|abbr=on}} or {{convert|15|mph|abbr=on}} faster than the congested traffic in the general purpose lanes. Bus drivers must be very attentive when taking the bus onto the shoulder, since that part of the road is only about one foot wider than the buses in many cases. To help with this issue, researchers at the University of Minnesota helped rig up a bus with a [[lane-keep system]], along with a [[heads-up display]] connected to a [[radar]] system to alert the driver of any obstacles. The technology was an adaptation of a system previously tested with drivers of [[snowplow]]s and made some headlines in the early 2000s. This system will be more widely deployed under the Urban Partnership Agreement that assisted in the Marq2 project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upa.dot.gov/agreements/minneapolis.htm |title=Minneapolis Urban Partnership Agreement |work=Urban Partnership Agreement and Congestion Reduction Demonstration Programs |publisher=U.S. Department of Transportation |accessdate=2010-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100827130236/http://www.upa.dot.gov/agreements/minneapolis.htm |archivedate=2010-08-27 }}</ref>\n\n===Transit centers===\n\nMetro Transit operates service to 28 [[transit center]]s, which provide connection points for bus and rail service throughout the metropolitan area.\n\n===Park and rides===\n\nMetro Transit operates service to 79 [[park and ride]] lots and ramps, with a total of 13,829 parking spaces. These lots allow commuters to park their cars for free and take buses and trains to the downtown areas to avoid traffic congestion and parking fees.\n\n== Fleet ==\n=== Buses ===\n[[File:Metro Transit bus stop at Coffman Memorial Union.jpg|thumb|Metro Transit buses at Washington Avenue bus stop on north side of [[Coffman Memorial Union]] on the [[University of Minnesota]] East Bank campus.]]\nMetro Transit operates the [[Gillig Phantom]], [[Gillig Low Floor|Gillig Advantage]] (which comprises the majority of the fleet), [[New Flyer]] D60HF, D60LFR, Xcelsior XD60, and [[Motor Coach Industries|MCI]] D4500.\n\nIn the 2000s, most buses had a mostly white [[livery]] with a predominantly blue strip running horizontally along the side and a large white \u201cT\u201d inside a red circle on the roof. Diesel\u2013electric hybrid buses introduced toward the end of the decade spurred new color schemes, with yellow at the front and the blue line moved above the side windows. The METRO light-rail vehicles have a different color scheme: predominantly blue and white, with yellow on each end. Metro Transit also uses [[vehicle wrap]] advertising on some buses and light rail cars, creating a different appearance.\n\nAll of the buses are [[handicapped-accessible]], either using [[hydraulic]] lifts or a [[low-floor]] design. The Metropolitan Council also operates the Metro Mobility [[paratransit]] system for door-to-door transportation.\n\nAll Metro Transit buses and light- and heavy-rail trains have bike racks installed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metrotransit.org/bike-options.aspx |title=Metro Transit - Bike Options}}</ref>\n\n=== Rail ===\n{{main|Metro Transit rolling stock}}\n\n[[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]] [[Flexity Swift]] 27 vehicles are operated on the [[Blue Line (Minnesota)|Blue Line]] light rail line. There are also 59 [[Siemens S70]] vehicles operating on both the Blue and [[Green Line (Minnesota)|Green Line]] light rail lines.<ref>{{cite web|title=Central Corridor Contracts Awarded|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/stpaul/101524299.html|accessdate=20 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829080932/http://www.startribune.com/local/stpaul/101524299.html|archivedate=29 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=FTA Signs Agreement to Fund Central Corridor|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/index.php?id=44&no_cache=1&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=13180&cHash=00d875d42e|accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref> Rolling stock for the [[Northstar Line]] commuter rail line consists of [[Bombardier BiLevel Coach]]es pulled by [[MotivePower Industries|MotivePower]] [[MPI MPXpress|MP36]] locomotives.\n\n==See also==\n\nOpt-out and regional providers:\n*[[Maple Grove Transit]]\n*[[Minnesota Valley Transit Authority]]\n*[[Plymouth Metrolink]]\n*[[SouthWest Transit]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above External links/Sources by script-assisted edit-->\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.metrotransit.org/ Metro Transit]\n* [http://www.metrotransit.org/transit-police Metro Transit Police]\n* [https://www.metrotransit.org/system-map System map]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060929134020/http://www.metrocouncil.org/planning/transportation/transportation.htm Report on the Twin Cities Transit System]\n* {{cite news \n