{"title_page": "Davenport (electoral district)", "text_new": "{{short description|Federal electoral district of Canada}}\n{{about||the provincial electoral district|Davenport (provincial electoral district)|the [[South Australia]]n electoral district|Electoral district of Davenport}}\n{{Infobox Canada electoral district\n| name                = Davenport\n| province            = Ontario\n| image               = Davenport in relation to the other Toronto ridings (2015 boundaries).png\n| caption             = Davenport in relation to other electoral districts in Toronto (2013 boundaries)\n| fed-status          = active\n| fed-district-number = 35018\n| fed-created         = 1933\n| fed-abolished       = \n| fed-election-first  = 1935\n| fed-election-last   = 2019\n| fed-rep             = Julie Dzerowicz\n| fed-rep-link        = \n| fed-rep-party       = Liberal\n| fed-rep-party-link  = Liberal Party of Canada\n| demo-pop-ref        = <ref>[[#2016fed|Statistics Canada]]: 2017</ref>\n| demo-area-ref       = <ref>[[#2016fed|Statistics Canada]]: 2017</ref>\n| demo-electors-ref   = \n| demo-census-date    = [[Canada 2016 Census|2016]]\n| demo-pop            = 108473\n| demo-electors       = 79,822\n| demo-electors-date  = 2019\n| demo-area           = 12.08\n| demo-cd             = [[Toronto]]\n| demo-csd            = [[Toronto]]\n}}\n[[Image:Davenport Elections Canada map 35018 (2015 boundaries).gif|250px|thumb|right|Map of Davenport]]\n'''Davenport''' is a federal [[electoral district (Canada)|electoral district]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada, that has been represented in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] since 1935.\n\n==Demographics==\nThe Davenport riding has the highest percentage of ethnic Portuguese of all Canadian federal ridings (27.4%),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/prof/rel/Rp-eng.cfm?TABID=1&LANG=E&APATH=3&DETAIL=0&DIM=0&FL=A&FREE=0&GC=0&GID=653421&GK=0&GRP=1&PID=92634&PRID=0&PTYPE=89103&S=0&SHOWALL=0&SUB=0&Temporal=2006&THEME=80&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF=&D1=0&D2=0&D3=0&D4=0&D5=0&D6=0 |title=2Profile of Ethnic Origin and Visible Minorities for Canada, Provinces, Territories and Federal Electoral Districts (2003 Representation Order), 2006 Census  |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |accessdate=2012-12-02}}</ref> and the highest percentage of European immigrants (28.5%, of whom 25.0% are from Southern Europe, and 19.2% from Southern European countries other than Italy), in all of Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/tbt/Rp-eng.cfm?LANG=E&APATH=3&DETAIL=0&DIM=0&FL=A&FREE=0&GC=0&GID=0&GK=0&GRP=1&PID=89444&PRID=0&PTYPE=88971,97154&S=0&SHOWALL=0&SUB=0&Temporal=2006&THEME=72&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF= |title=Immigrant Status and Place of Birth (38), Sex (3) and Age Groups (10) for the Population of Canada, Provinces, Territories and Federal Electoral Districts (2003 Representation Order), 2006 Census - 20% Sample Data  |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |accessdate=2012-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2006/ref/dict/app-ann010-eng.cfm#appj9 |title=Appendix J Comparison of places of birth disseminated in 2006, 2001 and 1996 |publisher=2.statcan.ca |date=2009-11-20 |accessdate=2012-11-30}}</ref> It also has the highest percentage of native speakers of Portuguese (20.7%) and of Romance languages other than the French language of Canada (32.0%, with many Italian and Spanish).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/tbt-tt/Rp-eng.cfm?LANG=E&APATH=3&DETAIL=1&DIM=0&FL=A&FREE=0&GC=0&GID=0&GK=0&GRP=1&PID=103017&PRID=0&PTYPE=101955&S=0&SHOWALL=0&SUB=0&Temporal=2011&THEME=90&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF= |title=2011 Census of Canada: Topic-based tabulations &#124; Detailed Mother Tongue (232), Knowledge of Official Languages (5), Age Groups (17A) and Sex (3) for the Population Excluding Institutional Residents of Canada, Provinces, Territories and Federal Electoral Districts (2003 Representation Order), 2011 Census |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |accessdate=2012-11-16}}</ref> The same holds true for home language (Portuguese: 14.0%; non-French Romance languages: 21.2%, both Canadian riding records)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/tbt-tt/Rp-eng.cfm?TABID=1&LANG=E&APATH=3&DETAIL=1&DIM=0&FL=A&FREE=0&GC=0&GID=974887&GK=0&GRP=1&PID=103281&PRID=0&PTYPE=101955&S=0&SHOWALL=0&SUB=0&Temporal=2011&THEME=90&VID=0&VNAMEE=&VNAMEF=&D1=0&D2=0&D3=0&D4=0&D5=0&D6=0 |title=First Official Language Spoken (7), Detailed Language Spoken Most Often at Home (232), Age Groups (17A) and Sex (3) for the Population Excluding Institutional Residents of Canada, Provinces, Territories and Federal Electoral Districts (2003 Representation Order), 2011 Census |publisher=2.statcan.gc.ca |accessdate=2012-11-19}}</ref>\n\n:''According to the [[Canada 2016 Census]]; 2013 representation<ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=FED&Code1=35018&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&SearchText=Davenport&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1&type=0</ref><ref>https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=FED2013&Code1=35018&Data=Count&SearchText=Davenport&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1</ref>''\n\n'''Ethnic groups:''' 66.2% White, 6.4% Black, 5.9% Chinese, 5.4% Latin American, 4.2% South Asian, 2.6% Filipino, 2.2% Southeast Asian, 1.9% Aboriginal, 3.5% Other, 1.6% Multiple <br />\n'''Languages:''' 55.6% English, 16.9% Portuguese, 4.9% Spanish, 4.3% Italian, 2.6% Cantonese, 1.9% French, 1.7% Vietnamese, 1.4% Tagalog, 1.2% Mandarin<br />\n'''Religions (2011):''' 64.5% Christian (48.3% Catholic, 2.7% Christian Orthodox, 1.9% Anglican, 1.2% Pentecostal, 1.2% United Church, 9.0% Other), 3.4% Buddhist, 2.8% Muslim, 1.7% Jewish, 1.6% Hindu, 25.2% No religion <br />\n'''Median income (2015):''' $29,461 <br />\n'''Average income (2015):''' $40,586\n\n==Geography==\nThe district includes parts of west-end [[Toronto]], and includes the neighbourhoods of [[Caledonia-Fairbanks|Fairbank]], [[Oakwood-Vaughan]], [[St. Clair Gardens]], [[Corso Italia (Toronto)|Corso Italia]], [[Dovercourt-Wallace Emerson-Junction|Dovercourt Village]], [[Bloordale Village]], [[Bloorcourt Village]], [[Brockton Village]], the [[Junction Triangle]] and the western part of [[Little Portugal, Toronto|Rua Acores]].\n\n==History==\nThe federal electoral district was created in 1933 from parts of [[Parkdale (electoral district)|Parkdale]] and [[Toronto Northwest]] [[electoral district (Canada)|ridings]].\n\nThe federal [[Riding (country subdivision)#Canada|riding]] of Davenport has been one of the most consistently [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] ridings in Canada over the last century; until 2011, the last non-Liberal to be elected for the constituency was [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament]] [[Douglas Morton]] in 1958. Since then, Liberals [[Walter L. Gordon|Walter Gordon]] and [[Charles Caccia]] (who himself held the seat for nearly 40 years) won the seat by increasing margins, finally culminating in a 17,500-vote majority in 1993. Meanwhile, the opposition parties in the constituency were shifting, and the [[New Democratic Party (Canada)|New Democratic Party]] candidate beat the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] or [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]] candidate in every election since 1979.\n\nAfter the election of Paul Martin to the Liberal leadership in late 2003, Charles Caccia lost the nomination for the seat to local city councillor [[Mario Silva (politician)|Mario Silva]], who had signed up sufficient new members to oust the incumbent; this was an unpopular situation and was deeply resented by many in the local Liberal party, which, combined with redistricting, led to an overnight tripling of the NDP vote in the 2004 federal election.\n\nIn 2011, [[Andrew Cash]] of the New Democratic Party won the seat by a significant margin, becoming the first non-Liberal in over 50 years to represent the riding.\n\nThis riding lost a fraction of territory to [[Toronto\u2014St. Paul's]] during the [[Canadian federal electoral redistribution, 2012|2012 electoral redistribution]].\n\n==Members of Parliament==\n\nThis riding has elected the following [[Members of Parliament]]:\n\n{{CanMP}}\n{{CanMP nodata|Davenport<br />''Riding created from'' [[Parkdale (electoral district)|Parkdale]] ''and'' [[Toronto Northwest]]}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1935\n| ToYr = 1940\n| Assembly# = 18\n| CanParty = Conservative (historical)\n| RepName = John Ritchie MacNicol\n| RepTerms# = 3\n| PartyTerms# = 1\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1940\n| ToYr = 1945\n| Assembly# = 19\n| CanParty = National Government\n| PartyTerms# = 1\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1945\n| ToYr = 1949\n| Assembly# = 20\n| CanParty = PC\n| PartyTerms# = 1\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1949\n| ToYr = 1953\n| Assembly# = 21\n| CanParty = Liberal\n| RepName = Paul Hellyer\n| RepTerms# = 2\n| PartyTerms# = 2\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1953\n| ToYr = 1957\n| Assembly# = 22\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1957\n| ToYr = 1958\n| Assembly# = 23\n| CanParty = PC\n| RepName = Douglas Morton\n| RepTerms# = 2\n| PartyTerms# = 2\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1958\n| ToYr = 1962\n| Assembly# = 24\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1962\n| ToYr = 1963\n| Assembly# = 25\n| CanParty = Liberal\n| RepName = Walter L. Gordon\n| RepTerms# = 3\n| PartyTerms# = 16\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1963\n| ToYr = 1965\n| Assembly# = 26\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1965\n| ToYr = 1968\n| Assembly# = 27\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1968\n| ToYr = 1972\n| Assembly# = 28\n| RepName = Charles Caccia\n| RepTerms# = 10\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1972\n| ToYr = 1974\n| Assembly# = 29\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1974\n| ToYr = 1979\n| Assembly# = 30\n}}\n{{CanMP row\n| FromYr = 1979\n| ToYr = 1980\n| Assembly# = 31\n}}\n